# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: risk-modeling-finance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The Basel III requirements were published by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision in 2010, and began to be implemented in major countries in 2012.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Implementation of the Fundamental Review of the Trading Book (FRTB), published and revised between 2013 and 2019, has been completed only in some countries and is scheduled to be completed in others in 2025 and 2026.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Implementation of the Basel III: Finalising post-crisis reforms (also known as Basel 3.1 or Basel III Endgame), introduced in 2017, was extended several times, and will be phased-in by 2028.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In the U.S., an additional 1% is required for globally systemically important financial institutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] It also requires minimum Tier 1 capital of 6% at all times (beginning in 2015).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Common Tier 1 capital comprises shareholders equity (including **audited** profits), less deductions of accounting reserve that are not believed to be loss absorbing "today", including goodwill and other intangible assets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] To prevent the potential of double-counting of capital across the economy, bank's holdings of other bank shares are also deducted.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Tier 2 capital + Tier 1 capital is required to be above 8%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Leverage ratio is calculated by dividing Tier 1 capital by the bank's leverage exposure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The leverage exposure is the sum of the exposures of all on-balance sheet assets, 'add-ons' for derivative exposures and securities financing transactions (SFTs), and credit conversion factors for off-balance sheet items.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Basel III introduced a minimum leverage ratio of 3%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The U.S. established another ratio, the supplemental leverage ratio, defined as Tier 1 capital divided by total assets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] A minimum leverage ratio of 5% is required for large banks and systemically important financial institutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, from April 2020 until 31 March 2021, for financial institutions with more than $250 billion in consolidated assets, the calculation excluded U.S.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Treasury securities and deposits at Federal Reserve Banks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In the EU, the minimum bank leverage ratio is the same 3% as required by Basel III.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The UK requires a minimum leverage ratio, for banks with deposits greater than £50 billion, of 3.25%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] This higher minimum reflects the PRA's differing treatment of the leverage ratio, which excludes central bank reserves in 'Total exposure' of the calculation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Basel III introduced two required liquidity/funding ratios.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The **liquidity coverage ratio** requires banks to hold sufficient high-quality liquid assets to cover its total net cash outflows over 30 days under a stressed scenario.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] This was implemented because some adequately-capitalized banks faced difficulties because of poor liquidity management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The LCR consists of two parts: the numerator is the value of HQLA, and the denominator consists of the total net cash outflows over a specified stress period (total expected cash outflows minus total expected cash inflows).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Regulators can allow banks to dip below their required liquidity levels per the liquidity coverage ratio during periods of stress.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In 2014, the Federal Reserve Board of Governors approved a U.S. version of the liquidity coverage ratio, which had more stringent definitions of HQLA and total net cash outflows.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Certain privately issued mortgage backed securities are included in HQLA under Basel III but not under the U.S. rule.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Bonds and securities issued by financial institutions, which can become illiquid during a financial crisis, are not eligible under the U.S. rule.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The rule is also modified for banks that do not have at least $250 billion in total assets or at least $10 billion in on-balance sheet foreign exposure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The **Net stable funding ratio** requires banks to hold sufficient stable funding to exceed the required amount of stable funding over a one-year period of extended stress.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] A new framework for exposures to CCPs was introduced in 2017.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The standardised approach for counterparty credit risk (SA-CCR), which replaced the Current exposure method, became effective in 2017.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] SA-CCR is used to measure the potential future exposure of derivative transactions in the leverage exposure measure and non-modelled Risk Weighted Asset calculations.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Capital requirements for equity investments in hedge funds, managed funds, and investment funds were introduced in 2017.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] A framework for limiting large exposure to external and internal counterparties was implemented in 2018.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In the UK, as of 2024, the Bank of England was in the process of implementing the Basel III framework on large exposures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] A revised securitisation framework, effective in 2018, aims to address shortcomings in the Basel II securitisation framework and to strengthen the capital standards for securitisations held on bank balance sheets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The frameworks addresses the calculation of minimum capital needs for securitisation exposures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Basel III reclassifies physical gold from a Tier 3 asset to a Tier 1 asset.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] New standards for "interest rate risk in the banking book" (IRRBB) became effective in 2023.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Banks are required to calculate their exposures based on "economic value of equity" (EVE) and "net interest income" (NII) under a set of prescribed interest rate shock scenarios.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The standards thereby deal with the risks associated with a change in interest rates, including interest rate gaps, basis risk, yield curve risk, and option risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The bank's exposure to IRRBB is then equal to the largest negative change in EVE across all scenarios - in essence, the theoretical risk to the economic value of a bank's equity from a change in interest rates.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Following a Fundamental Review of the Trading Book, minimum capital requirements for market risk in the trading book are based on a better calibrated standardised approach or internal model approval (IMA) for an expected shortfall measure rather than, under Basel II, value at risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] On 15 April 2014, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS) released the final version of its "Supervisory Framework for Measuring and Controlling Large Exposures" (SFLE) that builds on longstanding BCBS guidance on credit exposure concentrations.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] On 11 March 2016, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision released the second of three proposals on public disclosure of regulatory metrics and qualitative data by banking institutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The proposal requires disclosures on market risk to be more granular for both the standardized approach and regulatory approval of internal models.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In January 2013, the BCBS extended not only the implementation schedule to 2019, but broadened the definition of liquid assets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In December 2017, the implementation of the market risk framework was delayed from 2019 to 2022.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Implementation of the Basel III: Finalising post-crisis reforms, the market risk framework, and the revised Pillar 3 disclosure requirements were extended several times and will be phased-in by 2028.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The Federal Reserve implemented the Basel III standards in the U.S., with some modifications, via a proposal first published in 2011.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Final rules on the liquidity coverage ratio were published in 2014.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The implementing act of the Basel III agreements in the European Union was Directive 2013/36/EU (CRD IV) and Regulation (EU) No.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] 575/2013 on prudential requirements for credit institutions and investment firms (CRR), which was approved in 2013 and replaced the Capital Requirements Directives (2006/48 and 2006/49).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] An OECD study, released on 17 February 2011, projected that all else equal, the medium-term impact of Basel III implementation on economic growth would be in the range of −0.05% to −0.15% per year due to increased bank lending spreads of 15 to as much as 50 basis points.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In June 2024, a study by PwC projected that implemented of the Basel III Endgame requirements would reduce economic growth in the U.S. by 56 basis points via reduced returns to bank shareholders and increased costs to consumers and businesses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] In the United States, higher capital requirements resulted in contractions in trading operations and the number of personnel employed on trading floors.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Academics criticized Basel III for continuing to allow large banks to calculate credit risk using internal models and for setting overall minimum capital requirements too low.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Opaque treatment of all derivatives contracts is also criticized.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Since derivatives present major unknowns in a crisis these are seen as major failings by some critics causing several to claim that the "too big to fail" status remains with respect to major derivatives dealers who aggressively took on risk of an event they did not believe would happen—but did.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] As Basel III does not absolutely require extreme scenarios that management flatly rejects to be included in stress testing this remains a vulnerability.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The Heritage Foundation argued that capitalization regulation is inherently fruitless due to these and similar problems and—despite an opposite ideological view of regulation—agree that "too big to fail" persists.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Basel III was also criticized as negatively affecting the stability of the financial system by increasing incentives of banks to game the regulatory framework.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] Notwithstanding the enhancement introduced by the Basel III standard, it argued that "markets often fail to discipline large banks to hold prudent capital levels and make sound investment decisions".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/basel-iii] The Institute of International Finance a Washington, D.C.–based, 450-member banking trade association, argued against the implementation of the accords, claiming it would hurt banks and economic growth and add to the paper burden and risk inhibition by banks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] To reduce the lender's credit risk, the lender may perform a credit check on the prospective borrower, may require the borrower to take out appropriate insurance, such as mortgage insurance, or seek security over some assets of the borrower or a guarantee from a third party.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] The lender can also take out insurance against the risk or on-sell the debt to another company.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] In general, the higher the risk, the higher will be the interest rate that the debtor will be asked to pay on the debt.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Credit risk mainly arises when borrowers are unable or unwilling to pay.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Significant resources and sophisticated programs are used to analyze and manage risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Some companies run a credit risk department whose job is to assess the financial health of their customers, and extend credit (or not) accordingly.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] They may use in-house programs to advise on avoiding, reducing and transferring risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] They also use the third party provided intelligence.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Nationally recognized statistical rating organizations provide such information for a fee.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] For large companies with liquidly traded corporate bonds or credit default swaps, bond yield spreads and credit default swap spreads indicate market participants assessments of credit risk and may be used as a reference point to price loans or trigger collateral calls.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Most lenders employ their models (credit scorecards) to rank potential and existing customers according to risk, and then apply appropriate strategies.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] With products such as unsecured personal loans or mortgages, lenders charge a higher price for higher-risk customers and vice versa.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] With revolving products such as credit cards and overdrafts, the risk is controlled through the setting of credit limits.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Some products also require collateral, usually an asset that is pledged to secure the repayment of the loan.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Credit scoring models also form part of the framework used by banks or lending institutions to grant credit to clients.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] For corporate and commercial borrowers, these models generally have qualitative and quantitative sections outlining various aspects of the risk including, but not limited to, operating experience, management expertise, asset quality, and leverage and liquidity ratios, respectively.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Once this information has been fully reviewed by credit officers and credit committees, the lender provides the funds subject to the terms and conditions presented within the contract (as outlined above).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Sovereign credit risk is the risk of a government being unwilling or unable to meet its loan obligations, or reneging on loans it guarantees.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Many countries have faced sovereign risk in the Great Recession.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] The existence of such risk means that creditors should take a two-stage decision process when deciding to lend to a firm based in a foreign country.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Firstly one should consider the sovereign risk quality of the country and then consider the firm's credit quality.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] The probability of rescheduling is an increasing function of debt service ratio, import ratio, the variance of export revenue and domestic money supply growth.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] The likelihood of rescheduling is a decreasing function of investment ratio due to future economic productivity gains.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Debt rescheduling likelihood can increase if the investment ratio rises as the foreign country could become less dependent on its external creditors and so be less concerned about receiving credit from these countries/investors.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] A counterparty risk, also known as a settlement risk or **counterparty credit risk** (CCR), is a risk that a counterparty will not pay as obligated on a bond, derivative, insurance policy, or other contract.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Financial institutions or other transaction counterparties may hedge or take out credit insurance or, particularly in the context of derivatives, require the posting of collateral.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Offsetting counterparty risk is not always possible, e.g. because of temporary liquidity issues or longer-term systemic reasons.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] Further, counterparty risk increases due to positively correlated risk factors; accounting for this correlation between portfolio risk factors and counterparty default in risk management methodology is not trivial.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] The capital requirement here is calculated using SA-CCR, the standardized approach for counterparty credit risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/credit-risk] This framework replaced both non-internal model approaches – Current Exposure Method (CEM) and Standardised Method (SM).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Expected shortfall is also called **conditional value at risk** (**CVaR**), **average value at risk** (**AVaR**), **tail value at risk** (**TVaR**), **conditional tail expectation** (**CTE**), **expected tail loss** (**ETL**), and **superquantile**.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] These names are often used interchangeably, although several definitions exist in the literature.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] These definitions coincide in many cases, but may differ for certain types of loss distributions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Risk measures are used both in mathematical finance and in actuarial science, and the value-at-risk and expected shortfall measures are often expressed using different sign conventions and tail conventions in these disciplines.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The discussion that follows takes the mathematical finance point of view.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] In mathematical finance, risk measures arise when considering the profit/loss distribution, i.e., payoff, for a financial portfolio, modeled as a random variable X .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This can take positive or negative values, and downside risk corresponds to quantiles with $\alpha$ close to 0.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] A risk threshold $\alpha \in [0,1]$ is selected, and $\operatorname {VaR} _{\alpha }(X)$ is defined to be the absolute value of the $\alpha$ quantile of X (ignoring some technicalities).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This is also the $1-\alpha$ quantile of $-X$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The expected shortfall at level $\alpha$ is then defined as the average value of $\operatorname {VaR} _{\gamma }(X)$ for $\gamma$ in the interval $[0,\alpha ]$ , i.e., it is the average VaR over all levels below $\alpha$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Expected shortfall is often considered preferable to VaR because it accounts for the severity of the failure, not only the chance of failure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Further, it is a coherent spectral measure of financial portfolio risk, while VaR is not.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This is a collection of mathematical properties, one of which ensures that diversification of a portfolio never leads to a higher measure of risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Viewing the value produced by a risk measure as a capital reserve requirement, ES at level $\alpha$ is always more conservative than VaR at the same level, i.e., ES is always at least as big as VaR at the same level.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] where $\operatorname {VaR} _{\gamma }$ is the value at risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Several other definitions appear in the literature under the names ES, TVaR, AVaR, CTE, and CVaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The formulation above as an integral of VaR values is coherent and well-defined in the general case.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Other definitions typically coincide under common assumptions such as continuity of the loss distribution, but may differ for distributions with atoms.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This formulation agrees with the general definition above when the distribution is continuous at $x_{\alpha }$ , but may differ for distributions having atoms at the quantile.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Indeed, the second term in the formula just preceding this one vanishes for random variables with continuous distribution functions, and this conditional expectation formula follows.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Some variation in definitions arise from the differing conventions used between, say, financial mathematics and actuarial science, where things written with one set of conventions can be translated into a context with different ones.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] But there is further inconsistency, with some cases of substantively different definitions used for the same term.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] For instance, Sweeting defines TVaR as the tail conditional expectation, whereas he defines expected shortfall as the scaled version $\alpha \operatorname {TVaR} _{\alpha }(X)$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] There are a number of related, but subtly different, formulations for TVaR in the literature.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] A common case in literature is to define TVaR and average value at risk as the same measure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Under some formulations, it is only equivalent to expected shortfall when the underlying distribution function is continuous at $\operatorname {VaR} _{\alpha }(X)$ , the value at risk of level $\alpha$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] where ${\mathcal {Q}}_{\alpha }$ is the set of probability measures which are absolutely continuous to the physical measure P such that ${\frac {dQ}{dP}}\leq \alpha ^{-1}$ almost surely.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Note that ${\frac {dQ}{dP}}$ is the Radon–Nikodym derivative of Q with respect to P .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Expected shortfall can be generalized to a general class of coherent risk measures on $L^{p}$ spaces (Lp space) with a corresponding dual characterization in the corresponding $L^{q}$ dual space.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The domain can be extended for more general Orlicz Hearts.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the underlying distribution for X is a continuous distribution then the expected shortfall is equivalent to the tail conditional expectation defined by $\operatorname {TCE} _{\alpha }(X)=E[-X\mid X\leq -\operatorname {VaR} _{\alpha }(X)]$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Informally, and non-rigorously, this equation amounts to saying "in case of losses so severe that they occur only alpha percent of the time, what is our average loss".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If we believe our average loss on the worst 5% of the possible outcomes for our portfolio is EUR 1000, then we could say our expected shortfall is EUR 1000 for the 5% tail.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Now assume that we paid 100 at the beginning of the period for this portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] To see how these values were calculated, consider the calculation of $\operatorname {ES} _{0.05}$ , the expectation in the worst 5% of cases.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] These cases belong to (are a subset of) row 1 in the profit table, which have a profit of −100 (total loss of the 100 invested).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The expected profit for these cases is −100.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Now consider the calculation of $\operatorname {ES} _{0.20}$ , the expectation in the worst 20 out of 100 cases.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] These cases are as follows: 10 cases from row one, and 10 cases from row two (note that 10+10 equals the desired 20 cases).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] For row 1 there is a profit of −100, while for row 2 a profit of −20.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] We select as many rows starting from the top as are necessary to give a cumulative probability of q and then calculate an expectation over those cases.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] In general, the last row selected may not be fully used (for example in calculating $-\operatorname {ES} _{0.20}$ we used only 10 of the 30 cases per 100 provided by row 2).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] As a final example, calculate $-\operatorname {ES} _{1}$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The value at risk (VaR) is given below for comparison.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The expected shortfall $\operatorname {ES} _{q}$ increases as q decreases.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] The 100%-quantile expected shortfall $\operatorname {ES} _{1}$ equals negative of the expected value of the portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] For a given portfolio, the expected shortfall $\operatorname {ES} _{q}$ is greater than or equal to the Value at Risk $\operatorname {VaR} _{q}$ at the same q level.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Expected shortfall, in its standard form, is known to lead to a generally non-convex optimization problem.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] However, it is possible to transform the problem into a linear program and find the global solution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This property makes expected shortfall a cornerstone of alternatives to mean-variance portfolio optimization, which account for the higher moments (e.g., skewness and kurtosis) of a return distribution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Suppose that we want to minimize the expected shortfall of a portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Rockafellar/Uryasev proved that $F_{\alpha }(w,\gamma )$ is convex with respect to $\gamma$ and is equivalent to the expected shortfall at the minimum point.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] To numerically compute the expected shortfall for a set of portfolio returns, it is necessary to generate J simulations of the portfolio constituents; this is often done using copulas.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Using standard methods, it is then easy to find the portfolio that minimizes expected shortfall.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Closed-form formulas exist for calculating the expected shortfall when the payoff of a portfolio X or a corresponding loss $L=-X$ follows a specific continuous distribution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] Typical values of ${\textstyle \alpha }$ in this case are 5% and 1%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the loss of a portfolio L follows the normal distribution, the expected shortfall is equal to $\operatorname {ES} _{\alpha }(L)=\mu +\sigma {\frac {\varphi (\Phi ^{-1}(\alpha ))}{1-\alpha }}$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the loss of a portfolio L follows generalized Student's t-distribution, the expected shortfall is equal to $\operatorname {ES} _{\alpha }(L)=\mu +\sigma {\frac {\nu +(\mathrm {T} ^{-1}(\alpha ))^{2}}{\nu -1}}{\frac {\tau (\mathrm {T} ^{-1}(\alpha ))}{1-\alpha }}$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the payoff of a portfolio X follows the Laplace distribution with the p.d.f.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] then the expected shortfall is equal to $\operatorname {ES} _{\alpha }(X)=-\mu +b(1-\ln 2\alpha )$ for $\alpha \leq 0.5$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the loss of a portfolio L follows the logistic distribution, the expected shortfall is equal to $\operatorname {ES} _{\alpha }(L)=\mu +s{\frac {-\alpha \ln \alpha -(1-\alpha )\ln(1-\alpha )}{1-\alpha }}$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] If the loss of a portfolio L follows the GPD with p.d.f.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] As the incomplete beta function is defined only for positive arguments, for a more generic case the expected shortfall can be expressed with the hypergeometric function: $\operatorname {ES} _{\alpha }(X)=1-{\frac {e^{\mu }\alpha ^{s}}{s+1}}{_{2}F_{1}}(s,s+1;s+2;\alpha )$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] where $_{2}F_{1}$ is the hypergeometric function.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/expected-shortfall] This is not a time-consistent risk measure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The capital requirement for market risk is addressed under a revised framework known as "Fundamental Review of the Trading Book" (FRTB).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] All businesses take risks based on two factors: the probability an adverse circumstance will come about and the cost of such adverse circumstance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Risk management is then the study of how to control risks and balance the possibility of gains.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] For a discussion of the practice of (market) risk management in banks, investment firms, and corporates more generally see Financial risk management § Application.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] As with other forms of risk, the potential loss amount due to market risk may be measured in several ways or conventions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Traditionally, one convention is to use value at risk (VaR).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The conventions of using VaR are well established and accepted in the short-term risk management practice.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] However, VaR contains a number of limiting assumptions that constrain its accuracy.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The first assumption is that the composition of the portfolio measured remains unchanged over the specified period.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Over short time horizons, this limiting assumption is often regarded as reasonable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] However, over longer time horizons, many of the positions in the portfolio may have been changed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The VaR of the unchanged portfolio is no longer relevant.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Other problematic issues with VaR is that it is not sub-additive, and therefore not a coherent risk measure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] As a result, other suggestions for measuring market risk is conditional value-at-risk (CVaR) that is coherent for general loss distributions, including discrete distributions and is sub-additive.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The variance covariance and historical simulation approach to calculating VaR assumes that historical correlations are stable and will not change in the future or breakdown under times of market stress.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] However these assumptions are inappropriate as during periods of high volatility and market turbulence, historical correlations tend to break down.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Intuitively, this is evident during a financial crisis where all industry sectors experience a significant increase in correlations, as opposed to an upward trending market.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] This phenomenon is also known as asymmetric correlations or asymmetric dependence.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Rather than using the historical simulation, Monte-Carlo simulations with well-specified multivariate models are an excellent alternative.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] For example, to improve the estimation of the variance-covariance matrix, one can generate a forecast of asset distributions via Monte-Carlo simulation based upon the Gaussian copula and well-specified marginals.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Allowing the modelling process to allow for empirical characteristics in stock returns such as auto-regression, asymmetric volatility, skewness, and kurtosis is important.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Not accounting for these attributes lead to severe estimation error in the correlation and variance-covariance that have negative biases (as much as 70% of the true values).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Estimation of VaR or CVaR for large portfolios of assets using the variance-covariance matrix may be inappropriate if the underlying returns distributions exhibit asymmetric dependence.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] In such scenarios, vine copulas that allow for asymmetric dependence (e.g., Clayton, Rotated Gumbel) across portfolios of assets are most appropriate in the calculation of tail risk using VaR or CVaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Besides, care has to be taken regarding the intervening cash flow, embedded options, changes in floating rate interest rates of the financial positions in the portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] They cannot be ignored if their impact can be large.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] In finance, **market exposure** (or **exposure**) is a measure of the proportion of money invested in the same industry sector.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] For example, a stock portfolio with a total worth of $500,000, with $100,000 in semiconductor industry stocks, would have a 20% exposure in "chip" stocks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The Basel Committee set revised minimum capital requirements for market risk in January 2016.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] In the United States, a section on market risk is mandated by the SEC in all annual reports submitted on Form 10-K.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The company must detail how its results may depend directly on financial markets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] This is designed to show, for example, an investor who believes he is investing in a normal milk company, that the company is also carrying out non-dairy activities such as investing in complex derivatives or foreign exchange futures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] Physical investments face market risks as well, for example real capital such as real estate can lose market value and cost components such as fuel costs can fluctuate with market prices.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] On the other hand, some investments in physical capital can reduce risk and the value of the risk reduction can be estimated with financial calculation methods, just as market risk in financial markets is estimated.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] For example energy efficiency investments, in addition to reducing fuel costs, reduce exposure fuel price risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] As less fuel is consumed, a smaller cost component is susceptible to fluctuations in fuel prices.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/market-risk] The value of this risk reduction can be calculated using the Tuominen-Seppänen method and its value has been shown to be approximately 10% compared to direct cost savings for a typical energy efficient building.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Two types of events are analyzed in risk management: risks and opportunities.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Negative events can be classified as risks while positive events are classified as opportunities.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk management standards have been developed by various institutions, including the Project Management Institute, the National Institute of Standards and Technology, actuarial societies, and International Organization for Standardization.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Methods, definitions and goals vary widely according to whether the risk management method is in the context of project management, security, engineering, industrial processes, financial portfolios, actuarial assessments, or public health and safety.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Certain risk management standards have been criticized for having no measurable improvement on risk, whereas the confidence in estimates and decisions seems to increase.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The opposite of these strategies can be used to respond to opportunities (uncertain future states with benefits).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk analysts support the technical side of the organization's risk management approach: once risk data has been compiled and evaluated, analysts share their findings with their managers, who use those insights to decide among possible solutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] See also Chief Risk Officer, internal audit, and Financial risk management § Corporate finance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk is defined as the possibility that an event will occur that adversely affects the achievement of an objective.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Uncertainty, therefore, is a key aspect of risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk management appears in scientific and management literature since the 1920s.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] It became a formal science in the 1950s, when articles and books with "risk management" in the title also appear in library searches.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Most of research was initially related to finance and insurance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] One popular standard clarifying vocabulary used in risk management is *ISO Guide 31073:2022*, "Risk management — Vocabulary".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Ideally in risk management, a prioritization process is followed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Whereby the risks with the greatest loss (or impact) and the greatest probability of occurring are handled first.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risks with lower probability of occurrence and lower loss are handled in descending order.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In practice the process of assessing overall risk can be tricky, and organisation has to balance resources used to mitigate between risks with a higher probability but lower loss, versus a risk with higher loss but lower probability.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Opportunity cost represents a unique challenge for risk managers.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] It can be difficult to determine when to put resources toward risk management and when to use those resources elsewhere.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Again, ideal risk management optimises resource usage (spending, manpower etc), and also minimizes the negative effects of risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Opportunities first appear in academic research or management books in the 1990s.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The first PMBoK Project Management Body of Knowledge draft of 1987 doesn't mention opportunities at all.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Modern project management school recognize the importance of opportunities.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Opportunities have been included in project management literature since the 1990s, e.g. in PMBoK, and became a significant part of project risk management in the years 2000s, when articles titled "opportunity management" also begin to appear in library searches.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Opportunity management thus became an important part of risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Modern risk management theory deals with all types of external events, both positive and negative.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Positive risks are called *opportunities*.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Similar to risks, opportunities have specific mitigation strategies: exploit, share, enhance, or ignore.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In practice, risks are considered "usually negative".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk-related research and practice focus significantly more on threats than on opportunities.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This can lead to negative phenomena such as target fixation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Assess the vulnerability of critical assets to specific threats.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Determine the risk (i.e. the expected likelihood and consequences of specific attacks on specific assets).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Identify Risks** – identifying individual project risks as well as sources.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Perform Qualitative Risk Analysis** – prioritizing individual project risks by assessing probability and impact.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Perform Quantitative Risk Analysis** – numerical analysis of the effects.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Plan Risk Responses** – developing options, selecting strategies and actions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Implement Risk Responses** – implementing agreed-upon risk response plans.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In the 4th Ed. of PMBoK, this process was included as an activity in the Monitor and Control process, but was later separated as a distinct process in PMBoK 6th Ed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] **Monitor Risks** – monitoring the implementation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This process was known as Monitor and Control in the previous PMBoK 4th Ed., when it also included the "*Implement Risk Responses*" process.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Benoit Mandelbrot distinguished between "mild" and "wild" risk and argued that risk assessment and management must be fundamentally different for the two types of risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Mild risk follows normal or near-normal probability distributions, is subject to regression to the mean and the law of large numbers, and is therefore relatively predictable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Wild risk follows fat-tailed distributions, e.g., Pareto or power-law distributions, is subject to regression to the tail (infinite mean or variance, rendering the law of large numbers invalid or ineffective), and is therefore difficult or impossible to predict.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] A common error in risk assessment and management is to underestimate the wildness of risk, assuming risk to be mild when in fact it is wild, which must be avoided if risk assessment and management are to be valid and reliable, according to Mandelbrot.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] After establishing the context, the next step in the process of managing risk is to identify potential risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risks concern events that, when triggered, cause problems or benefits.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Therefore, risk identification can begin either with the sources of problems and those of competitors (benefits) or with the consequences of the problems.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Some examples of risk sources are: stakeholders of a project, employees of a company or the weather over an airport.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] When either source or problem is known, the events that a source may trigger or the events that can lead to a problem can be investigated.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example: stakeholders withdrawing during a project may endanger funding of the project; confidential information may be stolen by employees even within a closed network; lightning striking an aircraft during takeoff may make all people on board immediate casualties.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The chosen method of identifying risks may depend on culture, industry practice and compliance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The identification methods are formed by templates or the development of templates for identifying source, problem or event.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Once risks have been identified, they must then be assessed as to their potential severity of impact (generally a negative impact, such as damage or loss) and to the probability of occurrence.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] These quantities can be either simple to measure, in the case of the value of a lost building, or impossible to know for sure in the case of an unlikely event, the probability of occurrence of which is unknown.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Therefore, in the assessment process it is critical to make the best educated decisions in order to properly prioritize the implementation of the risk management plan.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Even a short-term positive improvement can have long-term negative impacts.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] A highway is widened to allow more traffic.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] More traffic capacity leads to greater development in the areas surrounding the improved traffic capacity.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Over time, traffic thereby increases to fill available capacity.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Turnpikes thereby need to be expanded in a seemingly endless cycles.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] There are many other engineering examples where expanded capacity (to do any function) is soon filled by increased demand.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Since expansion comes at a cost, the resulting growth could become unsustainable without forecasting and management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The fundamental difficulty in risk assessment is determining the rate of occurrence since statistical information is not available on all kinds of past incidents and is particularly scanty in the case of catastrophic events, simply because of their infrequency.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Furthermore, evaluating the severity of the consequences (impact) is often quite difficult for intangible assets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Asset valuation is another question that needs to be addressed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Thus, best educated opinions and available statistics are the primary sources of information.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Nevertheless, risk assessment should produce such information for senior executives of the organization that the primary risks are easy to understand and that the risk management decisions may be prioritized within overall company goals.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Thus, there have been several theories and attempts to quantify risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Periodically re-assess risks that are accepted in ongoing processes as a normal feature of business operations and modify mitigation measures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Later research has shown that the financial benefits of risk management are less dependent on the formula used but are more dependent on the frequency and how risk assessment is performed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In business it is imperative to be able to present the findings of risk assessments in financial, market, or schedule terms.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] (IBM, 1970) proposed a formula for presenting risks in financial terms.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The Courtney formula was accepted as the official risk analysis method for the US governmental agencies.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The formula proposes calculation of ALE (annualized loss expectancy) and compares the expected loss value to the security control implementation costs (cost–benefit analysis).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Planning for risk management uses four essential techniques.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Under the acceptance technique, the business intentionally assumes risks without financial protections in the hopes that possible gains will exceed prospective losses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The transfer approach shields the business from losses by shifting risks to a third party, frequently in exchange for a fee, while the third-party benefits from the project.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] By choosing not to participate in high-risk ventures, the avoidance strategy avoids losses but also loses out on possibilities.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Last but not least, the reduction approach lowers risks by implementing strategies like insurance, which provides protection for a variety of asset classes and guarantees reimbursement in the event of losses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Ideal use of these risk control strategies may not be possible.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Some of them may involve trade-offs that are not acceptable to the organization or person making the risk management decisions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Another source, from the US Department of Defense (see link), Defense Acquisition University, calls these categories ACAT, for Avoid, Control, Accept, or Transfer.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This use of the ACAT acronym is reminiscent of another ACAT (for Acquisition Category) used in US Defense industry procurements, in which Risk Management figures prominently in decision making and planning.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Similarly to risks, opportunities have specific mitigation strategies: exploit, share, enhance, ignore.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This includes not performing an activity that could present risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Refusing to purchase a property or business to avoid legal liability is one such example.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Avoiding airplane flights for fear of hijacking.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Avoidance may seem like the answer to all risks, but avoiding risks also means losing out on the potential gain that accepting (retaining) the risk may have allowed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Not entering a business to avoid the risk of loss also avoids the possibility of earning profits.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Increasing risk regulation in hospitals has led to avoidance of treating higher risk conditions, in favor of patients presenting with lower risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk reduction or "optimization" involves reducing the severity of the loss or the likelihood of the loss from occurring.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, sprinklers are designed to put out a fire to reduce the risk of loss by fire.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This method may cause a greater loss by water damage and therefore may not be suitable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Halon fire suppression systems may mitigate that risk, but the cost may be prohibitive as a strategy.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Acknowledging that risks can be positive or negative, optimizing risks means finding a balance between negative risk and the benefit of the operation or activity; and between risk reduction and effort applied.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] By effectively applying Health, Safety and Environment (HSE) management standards, organizations can achieve tolerable levels of residual risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Modern software development methodologies reduce risk by developing and delivering software incrementally.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Early methodologies suffered from the fact that they only delivered software in the final phase of development; any problems encountered in earlier phases meant costly rework and often jeopardized the whole project.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] By developing in iterations, software projects can limit effort wasted to a single iteration.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Outsourcing could be an example of risk sharing strategy if the outsourcer can demonstrate higher capability at managing or reducing risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, a company may outsource only its software development, the manufacturing of hard goods, or customer support needs to another company, while handling the business management itself.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This way, the company can concentrate more on business development without having to worry as much about the manufacturing process, managing the development team, or finding a physical location for a center.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Also, implanting controls can also be an option in reducing risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Controls that either detect causes of unwanted events prior to the consequences occurring during use of the product, or detection of the root causes of unwanted failures that the team can then avoid.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Controls may focus on management or decision-making processes.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] All these may help to make better decisions concerning risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The term 'risk transfer' is often used in place of risk-sharing in the mistaken belief that you can transfer a risk to a third party through insurance or outsourcing.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In practice, if the insurance company or contractor go bankrupt or end up in court, the original risk is likely to still revert to the first party.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, a personal injuries insurance policy does not transfer the risk of a car accident to the insurance company.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The risk still lies with the policyholder namely the person who has been in the accident.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The insurance policy simply provides that if an accident (the event) occurs involving the policyholder then some compensation may be payable to the policyholder that is commensurate with the suffering/damage.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Methods of managing risk fall into multiple categories.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk-retention pools are technically retaining the risk for the group, but spreading it over the whole group involves transfer among individual members of the group.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This is different from traditional insurance, in that no premium is exchanged between members of the group upfront, but instead, losses are assessed to all members of the group.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk retention involves accepting the loss, or benefit of gain, from a risk when the incident occurs.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] True self-insurance falls in this category.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk retention is a viable strategy for small risks where the cost of insuring against the risk would be greater over time than the total losses sustained.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] All risks that are not avoided or transferred are retained by default.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This includes risks that are so large or catastrophic that either they cannot be insured against or the premiums would be infeasible.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] War is an example since most property and risks are not insured against war, so the loss attributed to war is retained by the insured.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Also any amounts of potential loss (risk) over the amount insured is retained risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This may also be acceptable if the chance of a very large loss is small or if the cost to insure for greater coverage amounts is so great that it would hinder the goals of the organization too much.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Select appropriate controls or countermeasures to mitigate each risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk mitigation needs to be approved by the appropriate level of management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For instance, a risk concerning the image of the organization should have top management decision behind it whereas IT management would have the authority to decide on computer virus risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The risk management plan should propose applicable and effective security controls for managing the risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, an observed high risk of computer viruses could be mitigated by acquiring and implementing antivirus software.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] A good risk management plan should contain a schedule for control implementation and responsible persons for those actions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] There are four basic steps of risk management plan, which are threat assessment, vulnerability assessment, impact assessment and risk mitigation strategy development.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] According to ISO/IEC 27001, the stage immediately after completion of the risk assessment phase consists of preparing a Risk Treatment Plan, which should document the decisions about how each of the identified risks should be handled.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Mitigation of risks often means selection of security controls, which should be documented in a Statement of Applicability, which identifies which particular control objectives and controls from the standard have been selected, and why.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Implementation involves executing all planned methods for mitigating the effects of risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This includes purchasing insurance policies for risks that have been decided to be transferred to an insurer, avoiding all risks that can be avoided without compromising the entity's goals, reducing other risks, and retaining the remainder.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Initial risk management plans will never be perfect.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Practice, experience, and actual loss results will necessitate changes in the plan and contribute information to allow possible different decisions to be made in dealing with the risks being faced.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk analysis results and management plans should be updated periodically.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] 2. to evaluate the possible risk level changes in the business environment.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, information risks are a good example of rapidly changing business environment.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] There are various defined frameworks here, where every probable risk can have a pre-formulated plan to deal with its possible consequences (to ensure *contingency* if the risk becomes a *liability*).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Managers thus analyze and monitor both the internal and external environment facing the enterprise, addressing business risk generally, and any impact on the enterprise achieving its strategic goals.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] ERM thus overlaps various other disciplines - operational risk management, financial risk management etc. - but is differentiated by its strategic and long-term focus.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] ERM systems usually focus on safeguarding reputation, acknowledging its significant role in comprehensive risk management strategies.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The concept of "contractual risk management" emphasises the use of risk management techniques in contract deployment, i.e. managing the risks which are accepted through entry into a contract.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Norwegian academic Petri Keskitalo defines "contractual risk management" as "a practical, proactive and systematical contracting method that uses contract planning and governance to manage risks connected to business activities".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Greengard recommends using industry-standard contract language as much as possible to reduce risk as much as possible and rely on clauses which have been in use and subject to established court interpretation over a number of years.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] ESRM is a security program management approach that links security activities to an enterprise's mission and business goals through risk management methods.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The security leader's role in ESRM is to manage risks of harm to enterprise assets in partnership with the business leaders whose assets are exposed to those risks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For medical devices, risk management is a process for identifying, evaluating and mitigating risks associated with harm to people and damage to property or the environment.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk management is an integral part of medical device design and development, production processes and evaluation of field experience, and is applicable to all types of medical devices.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The evidence of its application is required by most regulatory bodies such as the US FDA.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The management of risks for medical devices is described by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in ISO 14971:2019, Medical Devices—The application of risk management to medical devices, a product safety standard.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The standard provides a process framework and associated requirements for management responsibilities, risk analysis and evaluation, risk controls and lifecycle risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Guidance on the application of the standard is available via ISO/TR 24971:2020.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The European version of the risk management standard was updated in 2009 and again in 2012 to refer to the Medical Devices Directive (MDD) and Active Implantable Medical Device Directive (AIMDD) revision in 2007, as well as the In Vitro Medical Device Directive (IVDD).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The differences include three "(informative)" Z Annexes that refer to the new MDD, AIMDD, and IVDD.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] These annexes indicate content deviations that include the requirement for risks to be reduced *as far as possible*, and the requirement that risks be mitigated by design and not by labeling on the medical device (i.e., labeling can no longer be used to mitigate risk).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] FTA analysis requires diagramming software.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] FMEA analysis can be done using a spreadsheet program.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] There are also integrated medical device risk management solutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Through a draft guidance, the FDA has introduced another method named "Safety Assurance Case" for medical device safety assurance analysis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The safety assurance case is structured argument reasoning about systems appropriate for scientists and engineers, supported by a body of evidence, that provides a compelling, comprehensible and valid case that a system is safe for a given application in a given environment.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] With the guidance, a safety assurance case is expected for safety critical devices (e.g. infusion devices) as part of the pre-market clearance submission, e.g.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In 2013, the FDA introduced another draft guidance expecting medical device manufacturers to submit cybersecurity risk analysis information.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Project risk management must be considered at the different phases of acquisition.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] At the beginning of a project, the advancement of technical developments, or threats presented by a competitor's projects, may cause a risk or threat assessment and subsequent evaluation of alternatives (see Analysis of Alternatives).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Megaprojects (sometimes also called "major programs") are large-scale investment projects, typically costing more than $1 billion per project.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Megaprojects include major bridges, tunnels, highways, railways, airports, seaports, power plants, dams, wastewater projects, coastal flood protection schemes, oil and natural gas extraction projects, public buildings, information technology systems, aerospace projects, and defense systems.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Megaprojects have been shown to be particularly risky in terms of finance, safety, and social and environmental impacts.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk management is therefore particularly pertinent for megaprojects and special methods and special education have been developed for such risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] It is important to assess risk in regard to natural disasters like floods, earthquakes, and so on.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Outcomes of natural disaster risk assessment are valuable when considering future repair costs, business interruption losses and other downtime, effects on the environment, insurance costs, and the proposed costs of reducing the risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction is a 2015 international accord that has set goals and targets for disaster risk reduction in response to natural disasters.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] There are regular International Disaster and Risk Conferences in Davos to deal with integral risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Several tools can be used to assess risk and risk management of natural disasters and other climate events, including geospatial modeling, a key component of land change science.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This modeling requires an understanding of geographic distributions of people as well as an ability to calculate the likelihood of a natural disaster occurring.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The management of risks to persons and property in wilderness and remote natural areas has developed with increases in outdoor recreation participation and decreased social tolerance for loss.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Organizations providing commercial wilderness experiences can now align with national and international consensus standards for training and equipment such as ANSI/NASBLA 101-2017 (boating), UIAA 152 (ice climbing tools), and European Norm 13089:2015 + A1:2015 (mountaineering equipment).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The Association for Experiential Education offers accreditation for wilderness adventure programs.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The Wilderness Risk Management Conference provides access to best practices, and specialist organizations provide wilderness risk management consulting and training.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] One popular models for risk assessment is the Risk Assessment and Safety Management (RASM) Model developed by Rick Curtis, author of The Backpacker's Field Manual.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The formula for the RASM Model is: Risk = Probability of Accident × Severity of Consequences.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The RASM Model weighs negative risk—the potential for loss, against positive risk—the potential for growth.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] IT risk is a risk related to information technology.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] This is a relatively new term due to an increasing awareness that information security is simply one facet of a multitude of risks that are relevant to IT and the real world processes it supports.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] "Cybersecurity is tied closely to the advancement of technology.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] It lags only long enough for incentives like black markets to evolve and new exploits to be discovered.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] ISACA's *Risk IT* framework ties IT risk to enterprise risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] IT risk management includes "incident handling", an action plan for dealing with intrusions, cyber-theft, denial of service, fire, floods, and other security-related events.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] According to the SANS Institute, it is a six step process: Preparation, Identification, Containment, Eradication, Recovery, and Lessons Learned.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Operational risk management (ORM) is the oversight of operational risk, including the risk of loss resulting from: inadequate or failed internal processes and systems; human factors; or external events.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Given the nature of operations, ORM is typically a "continual" process, and will include ongoing risk assessment, risk decision making, and the implementation of risk controls.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For the offshore oil and gas industry, operational risk management is regulated by the safety case regime in many countries.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Further, diagrammatic representations of hazardous events are often expected by governmental regulators as part of risk management in safety case submissions; these are known as **bow-tie diagrams** (see Network theory in risk assessment).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The technique is also used by organisations and regulators in mining, aviation, health, defence, industrial and finance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The principles and tools for quality risk management are increasingly being applied to different aspects of pharmaceutical quality systems.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk management is also applied to the assessment of microbiological contamination in relation to pharmaceutical products and cleanroom manufacturing environments.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Supply chain risk management (SCRM) aims at maintaining supply chain continuity in the event of scenarios or incidents which could interrupt normal business and hence profitability.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risks to the supply chain range from everyday to exceptional, including unpredictable natural events (such as tsunamis and pandemics) to counterfeit products, and reach across quality, security, to resiliency and product integrity.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Mitigation of these risks can involve various elements of the business including logistics and cybersecurity, as well as the areas of finance and operations.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Travel risk management is concerned with how organisations assess the risks to their staff when travelling, especially when travelling overseas.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] In the field of international standards, ISO 31030:2021 addresses good practice in travel risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The Global Business Travel Association's education and research arm, the GBTA Foundation. found in 2015 that most businesses covered by their research employed travel risk management protocols aimed at ensuring the safety and well-being of their business travelers.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Six key principles of travel risk awareness put forward by the association are preparation, awareness of surroundings and people, keeping a low profile, adopting an unpredictable routine, communications and layers of protection.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Traveler tracking using mobile tracking and messaging technologies had by 2015 become a widely used aspect of travel risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk communication is a complex cross-disciplinary academic field that is part of risk management and related to fields like crisis communication.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] The goal is to make sure that targeted audiences understand how risks affect them or their communities by appealing to their values.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk communication is particularly important in disaster preparedness, public health, and preparation for major global catastrophic risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For example, the impacts of climate change and climate risk effect every part of society, so communicating that risk is an important climate communication practice, in order for societies to plan for climate adaptation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Similarly, in pandemic prevention, understanding of risk helps communities stop the spread of disease and improve responses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk communication deals with possible risks and aims to raise awareness of those risks to encourage or persuade changes in behavior to relieve threats in the long term.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] On the other hand, crisis communication is aimed at raising awareness of a specific type of threat, the magnitude, outcomes, and specific behaviors to adopt to reduce the threat.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk communication in food safety is part of the risk analysis framework.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Together with risk assessment and risk management, risk communication aims to reduce foodborne illnesses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Food safety risk communication is an obligatory activity for food safety authorities in countries, which adopted the Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] Risk communication also exists on a smaller scale.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/risk-management] For instance, the risks associated with personal medical decisions have to be communicated to that individual along with their family.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In finance, a **stress test** is an analysis or simulation designed to determine the ability of a given financial instrument or financial institution to deal with an economic crisis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Instead of doing financial projection on a "best estimate" basis, a company or its regulators may do stress testing where they look at how robust a financial instrument is in certain crashes, a form of scenario analysis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The EBA's regulatory stress tests have been referred to as "a walk in the park" by Saxo Bank's Chief Economist.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] This emphasis on adequate, risk adjusted determination of capital has been further enhanced by modifications to banking regulations such as Basel II.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Stress testing models typically allow not only the testing of individual stressors, but also combinations of different events.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] There is also usually the ability to test the current exposure to a known historical scenario (such as the Russian debt default in 1998 or 9/11 attacks) to ensure the liquidity of the institution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In 2014, 25 banks failed in a stress test conducted by EBA.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] A **bank stress test** is a type of simulation that evaluates a financial institution’s ability to withstand adverse economic or market conditions by examining its balance sheet.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Large international banks began conducting internal stress tests in the early 1990s.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In 1996, the Basel Capital Accord was amended to require banks and investment firms to carry out stress tests to assess their ability to respond to significant market events.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Prior to the 2007–2008 financial crisis, however, stress testing was generally used only for internal risk management and self-assessment rather than for external regulatory oversight.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Beginning in 2007, governmental regulatory bodies became interested in conducting their own stress tests to insure the effective operation of financial institutions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Since then, stress tests have been routinely performed by financial regulators in different countries or regions, to ensure that the banks under their authority are engaging in practices likely to avoid negative outcomes.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In India, legislation was enacted in 2007 requiring banks to undergo regular stress tests.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In October 2012, U.S. regulators unveiled new rules expanding this practice by requiring the largest American banks to undergo stress tests twice per year, once internally and once conducted by the regulators.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Starting in 2014 midsized firms (i.e., those with $10–50 billion in assets) are also being required to conduct Dodd-Frank Act Stress Testing.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] In 2012, federal regulators also began recommending portfolio stress testing as a sound risk management practice for community banks or institutions that were too small to fall under Dodd-Frank's requirements.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) in an October 18, 2012, Bulletin recommends stress testing as a means to identify and quantify loan portfolio risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The FDIC made similar recommendations for community banks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Since the Federal Reserve began conducting Dodd–Frank Act Stress Tests, post-stress capital levels across large banking institutions have generally increased.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The Federal Reserve has also continued to expand its expectations over time by introducing more sophisticated and challenging stress-testing scenarios.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Statistician and risk analyst Nassim Taleb has advocated a different approach to stress testing saying that stress tests based on arbitrary numbers can be gamed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] A more effective test is to assess the fragility of a bank by applying one stress test and scaling it up, which provides an indicator of how sensitive a bank is to changes in economic conditions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Another form of financial stress testing is the stress testing of financial market infrastructure.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] As part of Central Banks' market infrastructure oversight functions, stress tests have been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Since ultimately, the Banks need to meet their obligations in Central Bank money held in payment systems that are commonly operated or closely supervised by central banks (e.g.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] CHAPS, FedWire, Target2, which are also referred to as large value payment systems), it is of great interest to monitor these systems' participants' (mainly banks) liquidity positions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The amount of liquidity held by banks on their accounts can be a lot less (and usually is) than the total value of transferred payments during a day.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The total amount of liquidity needed by banks to settle a given set of payments is dependent on the balancedness of the circulation of money from account to account (reciprocity of payments), the timing of payments and the netting procedures used.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The inability of some participants to send payments can cause severe falls in settlement ratios of payments.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The failure of one participant to send payments can have negative contagion effects on other participants' liquidity positions and their potential to send payments.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] By using stress tests it is possible to evaluate the short term effects of events such as bank failures or technical communication breakdowns that lead to the inability of chosen participants to send payments.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] These effects can be viewed as direct effects on the participant, but also as systemic contagion effects.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] How hard the other participants will be hit by a chosen failure scenario will be dependent on the available collateral and initial liquidity of participants, and their potential to bring in more liquidity.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Stress test conducted on payment systems help to evaluate the short term adequacy and sufficiency of the prevailing liquidity levels and buffers of banks, and the contingency measures of the studied payment systems.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] A financial stress test is only as good as the scenarios on which it is based.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Those designing stress tests must literally imagine possible futures that the financial system might face.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] As an exercise of the imagination, the stress test is limited by the imaginative capacities of those designing the stress test scenarios.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Sometimes, the stress test's designers fail to imagine plausible future scenarios, possibly because of professional peer pressure or groupthink within a profession or trade or because some things are just too horrible to imagine.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] For example, there was a failure by the great majority of financial experts to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] The successive financial stress tests conducted by the European Banking Authority and the Committee of European Banking Supervisors in 2009, 2010 and 2011 illustrate this dynamic.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/stress-test-financial] Those reviewing and using the results of stress tests must cast a critical eye on the scenarios used in the stress test.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For a given portfolio, time horizon, and probability *p*, the *p* VaR can be defined informally as the maximum possible loss during that time after excluding all worse outcomes whose combined probability is at most *p*.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This assumes mark-to-market pricing, and no trading in the portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For example, if a portfolio of stocks has a one-day 5% VaR of $1 million, that means that there is a 0.05 probability that the portfolio will fall in value by $1 million or more over a one-day period if there is no trading.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Informally, a loss of $1 million or more on this portfolio is expected on 1 day out of 20 days (because of 5% probability).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] More formally, *p* VaR is defined such that the probability of a loss greater than VaR is (at most) *p* while the probability of a loss less than VaR is (at least) *1-p*.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A loss which exceeds the VaR threshold is termed a "VaR breach".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For a fixed *p*, the *p* VaR does not assess the magnitude of loss when a VaR breach occurs and therefore is considered by some to be a questionable metric for risk management.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For instance, assume someone makes a bet that flipping a coin seven times will not give seven heads.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The terms are that he wins $100 if this does not happen (with probability 127/128) and he loses $12,700 if it does happen (with probability 1/128).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] That is, the possible loss amounts are $0 or $12,700.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The 1% VaR is then $0, because the probability of any loss at all is 1/128 which is less than 1%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] They are, however, exposed to a possible loss of $12,700 which can be expressed as the *p* VaR for any *p ≤ 0.78125% (1/128)*.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR has four main uses in finance: risk management, financial control, financial reporting and computing regulatory capital.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR is sometimes used in non-financial applications as well.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] However, it is a controversial risk management tool.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Important related ideas are economic capital, backtesting, stress testing, expected shortfall, and tail conditional expectation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Common parameters for VaR are 1% and 5% probabilities and one day and two week horizons, although other combinations are in use.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The reason for assuming normal markets and no trading, and to restricting loss to things measured in daily accounts, is to make the loss observable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In some extreme financial events it can be impossible to determine losses, either because market prices are unavailable or because the loss-bearing institution breaks up.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Some longer-term consequences of disasters, such as lawsuits, loss of market confidence and employee morale and impairment of brand names can take a long time to play out, and may be hard to allocate among specific prior decisions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR marks the boundary between normal days and extreme events.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Institutions can lose far more than the VaR amount; all that can be said is that they will not do so very often.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The probability level is about equally often specified as one minus the probability of a VaR break, so that the VaR in the example above would be called a one-day 95% VaR instead of one-day 5% VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This generally does not lead to confusion because the probability of VaR breaks is almost always small, certainly less than 50%.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Although it virtually always represents a loss, VaR is conventionally reported as a positive number.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A negative VaR would imply the portfolio has a high probability of making a profit, for example a one-day 5% VaR of negative $1 million implies the portfolio has a 95% chance of making more than $1 million over the next day.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Another inconsistency is that VaR is sometimes taken to refer to profit-and-loss at the end of the period, and sometimes as the maximum loss at any point during the period.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The original definition was the latter, but in the early 1990s when VaR was aggregated across trading desks and time zones, end-of-day valuation was the only reliable number so the former became the *de facto* definition.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] As people began using multiday VaRs in the second half of the 1990s, they almost always estimated the distribution at the end of the period only.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It is also easier theoretically to deal with a point-in-time estimate versus a maximum over an interval.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Therefore, the end-of-period definition is the most common both in theory and practice today.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The definition of VaR is nonconstructive; it specifies a property VaR must have, but not how to compute VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Moreover, there is wide scope for interpretation in the definition.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This has led to two broad types of VaR, one used primarily in risk management and the other primarily for risk measurement.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The distinction is not sharp, however, and hybrid versions are typically used in financial control, financial reporting and computing regulatory capital.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] To a risk manager, VaR is a system, not a number.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The system is run periodically (usually daily) and the published number is compared to the computed price movement in opening positions over the time horizon.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] There is never any subsequent adjustment to the published VaR, and there is no distinction between VaR breaks caused by input errors (including IT breakdowns, fraud and rogue trading), computation errors (including failure to produce a VaR on time) and market movements.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A frequentist claim is made that the long-term frequency of VaR breaks will equal the specified probability, within the limits of sampling error, and that the VaR breaks will be independent in time and independent of the level of VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This claim is validated by a backtest, a comparison of published VaRs to actual price movements.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In this interpretation, many different systems could produce VaRs with equally good backtests, but wide disagreements on daily VaR values.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For risk measurement a number is needed, not a system.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A Bayesian probability claim is made that given the information and beliefs at the time, the subjective probability of a VaR break was the specified level.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR is adjusted after the fact to correct errors in inputs and computation, but not to incorporate information unavailable at the time of computation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In this context, "backtest" has a different meaning.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Rather than comparing published VaRs to actual market movements over the period of time the system has been in operation, VaR is retroactively computed on scrubbed data over as long a period as data are available and deemed relevant.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The same position data and pricing models are used for computing the VaR as determining the price movements.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] When VaR is used for financial control or financial reporting it should incorporate elements of both.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For example, if a trading desk is held to a VaR limit, that is both a risk-management rule for deciding what risks to allow today, and an input into the risk measurement computation of the desk's risk-adjusted return at the end of the reporting period.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR can also be applied to governance of endowments, trusts, and pension plans.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Essentially, trustees adopt portfolio Values-at-Risk metrics for the entire pooled account and the diversified parts individually managed.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Instead of probability estimates they simply define maximum levels of acceptable loss for each.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Doing so provides an easy metric for oversight and adds accountability as managers are then directed to manage, but with the additional constraint to avoid losses within a defined risk parameter.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR utilized in this manner adds relevance as well as an easy way to monitor risk measurement control far more intuitive than Standard Deviation of Return.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A fund relying on the rule generally must comply with an outer limit on fund leverage risk based on value-at-risk, or “VaR.” This outer limit is based on a relative VaR test that compares the fund’s VaR to the VaR of a “designated reference portfolio” for that fund.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A fund generally can use either an index that meets certain requirements or the fund’s own securities portfolio (excluding derivatives transactions) as its designated reference portfolio.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] If the fund’s derivatives risk manager reasonably determines that a designated reference portfolio would not provide an appropriate reference portfolio for purposes of the relative VaR test, the fund would be required to comply with an absolute VaR test.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The fund’s VaR generally is not permitted to exceed 200% of the VaR of the fund’s designated reference portfolio under the relative VaR test or 20% of the fund’s net assets under the absolute VaR test.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Let X be a profit and loss distribution (loss negative and profit positive).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The VaR at level $\alpha \in (0,1)$ is the smallest number y such that the probability that $Y:=-X$ does not exceed y is at least $1-\alpha$ .
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This is the most general definition of VaR and the two identities are equivalent (indeed, for any real random variable X its cumulative distribution function $F_{X}$ is well defined).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] However this formula cannot be used directly for calculations unless we assume that X has some parametric distribution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Risk managers typically assume that some fraction of the bad events will have undefined losses, either because markets are closed or illiquid, or because the entity bearing the loss breaks apart or loses the ability to compute accounts.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Therefore, they do not accept results based on the assumption of a well-defined probability distribution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Nassim Taleb has labeled this assumption, "charlatanism".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] On the other hand, many academics prefer to assume a well-defined distribution, albeit usually one with fat tails.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This point has probably caused more contention among VaR theorists than any other.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The term "VaR" is used both for a risk measure and a risk metric.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Sources earlier than 1995 usually emphasize the risk measure, later sources are more likely to emphasize the metric.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The VaR risk measure defines risk as mark-to-market loss on a fixed portfolio over a fixed time horizon.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] There are many alternative risk measures in finance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Given the inability to use mark-to-market (which uses market prices to define loss) for future performance, loss is often defined (as a substitute) as change in fundamental value.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For example, if an institution holds a loan that declines in market price because interest rates go up, but has no change in cash flows or credit quality, some systems do not recognize a loss.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Also some try to incorporate the economic cost of harm not measured in daily financial statements, such as loss of market confidence or employee morale, impairment of brand names or lawsuits.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Rather than assuming a static portfolio over a fixed time horizon, some risk measures incorporate the dynamic effect of expected trading (such as a stop loss order) and consider the expected holding period of positions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The VaR risk metric summarizes the distribution of possible losses by a quantile, a point with a specified probability of greater losses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A common alternative metric is expected shortfall.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Supporters of VaR-based risk management claim the first and possibly greatest benefit of VaR is the improvement in systems and modeling it forces on an institution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Publishing a daily number, on-time and with specified statistical properties holds every part of a trading organization to a high objective standard.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Robust backup systems and default assumptions must be implemented.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Positions that are reported, modeled or priced incorrectly stand out, as do data feeds that are inaccurate or late and systems that are too-frequently down.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Anything that affects profit and loss that is left out of other reports will show up either in inflated VaR or excessive VaR breaks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The second claimed benefit of VaR is that it separates risk into two regimes.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Inside the VaR limit, conventional statistical methods are reliable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Relatively short-term and specific data can be used for analysis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Probability estimates are meaningful because there are enough data to test them.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In a sense, there is no true risk because these are a sum of many independent observations with a left bound on the outcome.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For example, a casino does not worry about whether red or black will come up on the next roulette spin.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Risk managers encourage productive risk-taking in this regime, because there is little true cost.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] People tend to worry too much about these risks because they happen frequently, and not enough about what might happen on the worst days.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Outside the VaR limit, all bets are off.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Risk should be analyzed with stress testing based on long-term and broad market data.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Probability statements are no longer meaningful.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Knowing the distribution of losses beyond the VaR point is both impossible and useless.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The risk manager should concentrate instead on making sure good plans are in place to limit the loss if possible, and to survive the loss if not.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Three to ten times VaR is the range for stress testing.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Institutions should be confident they have examined all the foreseeable events that will cause losses in this range, and are prepared to survive them.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] These events are too rare to estimate probabilities reliably, so risk/return calculations are useless.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Foreseeable events should not cause losses beyond ten times VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] If they do they should be hedged or insured, or the business plan should be changed to avoid them, or VaR should be increased.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It is hard to run a business if foreseeable losses are orders of magnitude larger than very large everyday losses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It is hard to plan for these events because they are out of scale with daily experience.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Another reason VaR is useful as a metric is due to its ability to compress the riskiness of a portfolio to a single number, making it comparable across different portfolios (of different assets).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Within any portfolio it is also possible to isolate specific positions that might better hedge the portfolio to reduce, and minimise, the VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR can be estimated either parametrically (for example, variance-covariance VaR or delta-gamma VaR) or nonparametrically (for examples, historical simulation VaR or resampled VaR).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Nonparametric methods of VaR estimation are discussed in Markovich and Novak.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A comparison of a number of strategies for VaR prediction is given in Kuester et al.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A McKinsey report published in May 2012 estimated that 85% of large banks were using historical simulation.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The other 15% used Monte Carlo methods (often applying a PCA decomposition).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Backtesting is the process to determine the accuracy of VaR forecasts vs. actual portfolio profit and losses.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A key advantage to VaR over most other measures of risk such as expected shortfall is the availability of several backtesting procedures for validating a set of VaR forecasts.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Early examples of backtests can be found in Christoffersen (1998), later generalized by Pajhede (2017), which models a "hit-sequence" of losses greater than the VaR and proceed to tests for these "hits" to be independent from one another and with a correct probability of occurring.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] E.g. a 5% probability of a loss greater than VaR should be observed over time when using a 95% VaR, these hits should occur independently.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A number of other backtests are available which model the time between hits in the hit-sequence, see Christoffersen and Pelletier (2004), Haas (2006), Tokpavi et al.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] (2014). and Pajhede (2017) As pointed out in several of the papers, the asymptotic distribution is often poor when considering high levels of coverage, e.g. a 99% VaR, therefore the parametric bootstrap method of Dufour (2006) is often used to obtain correct size properties for the tests.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Backtest toolboxes are available in Matlab, or R—though only the first implements the parametric bootstrap method.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The second pillar of Basel II includes a backtesting step to validate the VaR figures.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The problem of risk measurement is an old one in statistics, economics and finance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Financial risk management has been a concern of regulators and financial executives for a long time as well.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Retrospective analysis has found some VaR-like concepts in this history.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] But VaR did not emerge as a distinct concept until the late 1980s.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The triggering event was the stock market crash of 1987.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This was the first major financial crisis in which a lot of academically-trained quants were in high enough positions to worry about firm-wide survival.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The crash was so unlikely given standard statistical models, that it called the entire basis of quant finance into question.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A reconsideration of history led some quants to decide there were recurring crises, about one or two per decade, that overwhelmed the statistical assumptions embedded in models used for trading, investment management and derivative pricing.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] These affected many markets at once, including ones that were usually not correlated, and seldom had discernible economic cause or warning (although after-the-fact explanations were plentiful).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Much later, they were named "Black Swans" by Nassim Taleb and the concept extended far beyond finance.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] If these events were included in quantitative analysis they dominated results and led to strategies that did not work day to day.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] If these events were excluded, the profits made in between "Black Swans" could be much smaller than the losses suffered in the crisis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR was developed as a systematic way to segregate extreme events, which are studied qualitatively over long-term history and broad market events, from everyday price movements, which are studied quantitatively using short-term data in specific markets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It was hoped that "Black Swans" would be preceded by increases in estimated VaR or increased frequency of VaR breaks, in at least some markets.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The extent to which this has proven to be true is controversial.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Abnormal markets and trading were excluded from the VaR estimate in order to make it observable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It is not always possible to define loss if, for example, markets are closed as after 9/11, or severely illiquid, as happened several times in 2008.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Losses can also be hard to define if the risk-bearing institution fails or breaks up.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A measure that depends on traders taking certain actions, and avoiding other actions, can lead to self reference.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It was well established in quantitative trading groups at several financial institutions, notably Bankers Trust, before 1990, although neither the name nor the definition had been standardized.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] There was no effort to aggregate VaRs across trading desks.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The financial events of the early 1990s found many firms in trouble because the same underlying bet had been made at many places in the firm, in non-obvious ways.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Since many trading desks already computed risk management VaR, and it was the only common risk measure that could be both defined for all businesses and aggregated without strong assumptions, it was the natural choice for reporting firmwide risk.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Morgan CEO Dennis Weatherstone famously called for a "4:15 report" that combined all firm risk on one page, available within 15 minutes of the market close.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Risk measurement VaR was developed for this purpose.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Morgan, which published the methodology and gave free access to estimates of the necessary underlying parameters in 1994.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] This was the first time VaR had been exposed beyond a relatively small group of quants.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Two years later, the methodology was spun off into an independent for-profit business now part of RiskMetrics Group (now part of MSCI).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Securities and Exchange Commission ruled that public corporations must disclose quantitative information about their derivatives activity.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Major banks and dealers chose to implement the rule by including VaR information in the notes to their financial statements.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Worldwide adoption of the Basel II Accord, beginning in 1999 and nearing completion today, gave further impetus to the use of VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR is the preferred measure of market risk, and concepts similar to VaR are used in other parts of the accord.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR has been controversial since it moved from trading desks into the public eye in 1994.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A famous 1997 debate between Nassim Taleb and Philippe Jorion set out some of the major points of contention.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In 2008 David Einhorn and Aaron Brown debated VaR in Global Association of Risk Professionals Review.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Einhorn compared VaR to "an airbag that works all the time, except when you have a car accident".
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] New York Times reporter Joe Nocera wrote an extensive piece Risk Mismanagement on January 4, 2009, discussing the role VaR played in the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] After interviewing risk managers (including several of the ones cited above) the article suggests that VaR was very useful to risk experts, but nevertheless exacerbated the crisis by giving false security to bank executives and regulators.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A powerful tool for professional risk managers, VaR is portrayed as both easy to misunderstand, and dangerous when misunderstood.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Taleb in 2009 testified in Congress asking for the banning of VaR for a number of reasons.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] One was that tail risks are non-measurable.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Another was that for anchoring reasons VaR leads to higher risk taking.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] VaR is not subadditive: VaR of a combined portfolio can be larger than the sum of the VaRs of its components.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For example, the average bank branch in the United States is robbed about once every ten years.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A single-branch bank has about 0.0004% chance of being robbed on a specific day, so the risk of robbery would not figure into one-day 1% VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It would not even be within an order of magnitude of that, so it is in the range where the institution should not worry about it, it should insure against it and take advice from insurers on precautions.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] The whole point of insurance is to aggregate risks that are beyond individual VaR limits, and bring them into a large enough portfolio to get statistical predictability.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It does not pay for a one-branch bank to have a security expert on staff.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] As institutions get more branches, the risk of a robbery on a specific day rises to within an order of magnitude of VaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] At that point it makes sense for the institution to run internal stress tests and analyze the risk itself.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] It will spend less on insurance and more on in-house expertise.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For a very large banking institution, robberies are a routine daily occurrence.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Losses are part of the daily VaR calculation, and tracked statistically rather than case-by-case.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A sizable in-house security department is in charge of prevention and control, the general risk manager just tracks the loss like any other cost of doing business.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] As portfolios or institutions get larger, specific risks change from low-probability/low-predictability/high-impact to statistically predictable losses of low individual impact.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] That means they move from the range of far outside VaR, to be insured, to near outside VaR, to be analyzed case-by-case, to inside VaR, to be treated statistically.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] By definition, VaR is a particular characteristic of the probability distribution of the underlying (namely, VaR is essentially a quantile).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] For a dynamic measure of risk, see Novak, ch.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Reporting a VaR that has not passed a backtest.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] Regardless of how VaR is computed, it should have produced the correct number of breaks (within sampling error) in the past.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A common violation of common sense is to estimate a VaR based on the unverified assumption that everything follows a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] However, it can be bounded by coherent risk measures like Conditional Value-at-Risk (CVaR) or entropic value at risk (EVaR).
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] CVaR is defined by average of VaR values for confidence levels between 0 and α.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] However VaR, unlike CVaR, has the property of being a robust statistic.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] A related class of risk measures is the 'Range Value at Risk' (RVaR), which is a robust version of CVaR.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] in which $M_{X}(z)$ is the moment-generating function of X at z.
[src:risk-modeling-finance/value-at-risk] In the above equations the variable X denotes the financial loss, rather than wealth as is typically the case.
